I have not yet had a successful print with this size on my Makerbot, mostly due to ABS curling -- something I hope my forthcoming HBP kit will solve. title: 2020 V-Slot Kossel Bottom Vertex with M3 Holes and Cutouts to Ease Warp

description.text:
This is a remix of a Kossel Frame Vertex designed to work with 2020 extrusion. Credit to "M3 holes and V-slot profile" by Sneq. The original part was designed to better fit v-slot profile to increase rigidity of the delta frame, but I often suffered from slight warping and peeling from the bed as the layer height increased on the bottom vertices. To help resolve the problem I added cutouts to reduce the warping that occurs as the bottom vertices are printed.

I have also remixed Sneq's original part by adding another set of top and bottom vertices to to fit extrusions that have an 8mm gap at the widest point of their v-slots. Make sure to measure and use the appropriate corners for your profile, and check out the M3 inserts I've designed for assembling your delta frame: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2369330

title: Wombot X Axis Digital Calipers Checker

description.text:
Anyone with X Axis of 2020 aluminium rail can use this tools, adjusting first your X axis, then if you like you can also adjust your bed as well.
X Axis Levelling:
I've find it best to just use an example setting on the Digital Caliper my was set at 10mm in the photo, leave it set at this and move your x axis to suit.

(You might need to alter the measurement if you have a different printer other than a Wombot.)

First I level my X axis very slow lowering it in 0.1mm increments, (Don't blame me if you damage anything). LOL be careful please.
If you're different on each side, disable the Stepper motor and screw up or down to suit so the end of Caliper just touch the Aluminium frame. Check both side to 2-3 times.
(Don't forget to disable the stepper motor while making adjustment each time.)

Bed Levelling:
Next move this tool so it at one end of your bed, attach it above one side of the bed (add the Key as well as this ensure it is fully on the 2020 aluminium) adjust the X axis up or down so the end of the Digital Caliper comes to rest just touch the bed, even use a scrap of paper so you don't damage your bed surface.
Slowly move the bed if you have paper under the tip of Caliper hold it and the bed together, if it starts to bind up, STOP and tighten the bed screw on the close side to the Calipers, if you find it has free up, proceed the full width of the bed, if it bind up again, do the same procedure.
Next swap sides, (if the tools doesn't fit make adjustment to the bed, by lowering it down via the bed screws) then bring the bed back up so it touches the underside of Caliper end, check across bed the same as you did on the other side, and make adjustments.
Double check the bed 2 - 3 times as you'll be amazed the other side has change and might need to be raised.

Anyway it should help those out who own Digital Calipers and have sometime set aside to calibrate their X Axis and bed properly within 5 - 10 minutes.

Also make sure to not overtighten the screw, just need to be firm and not loose.

List of extra parts you need for the tools
1./ 4mm bolt 10mm long
2./ 4mm washer
3./ 4mm nut
Happy levelling, hope you get the result you're looking for with your X axis and bed setup properly.
Note You will probably need to readjust your Z - offset again as I'm sure it will be out for sure now, bring the extruder down so it just touches a piece of paper, then add or subtract the different, from what you have currently.
P.S. don't forget to press "Store Memory" once finished altering the Z - offset.

Customizable fidget spinner for all sizes of bearings/weights. Can accommodate both cylinders and spheres as weights.

When using balls as weights, you must print in halves and glue together in order to insert the balls. Most slicers will allow you to do this by translating the model in Z below the bed by half the print height; anything below the bed plane will not be printed.

Add about .3mm to the diameter of any sphere weights to allow the printed halves to join easily. No clearance is necessary for cylinder weights (bearings), although that will make for an extremely tight fit.

comments.author: skitcher

comments.text: With most slicers, you can split any print horizontally by adjusting the model so that it drops below the bed plane. So, for the default case, drop the model by -3.5mm in the Z axis. Print twice, glue together. I have found it difficult to precisely align the two halves using superglue as the set time is so fast. If you're using balls, it is easier because you need to put the balls in before gluing and they will align the halves. Try not to get any glue on the balls. For bearings, if you don't want to risk gluing the weight bearings in place, use a long setting glue like E6000. It is not strictly necessary to glue the halves together because at least the central bearing will hold them together, but it may leave a visible gap if you don't.

title: Z Brace Pi Zero W & Cam- adjustable, snap-together, toolless mount system

description.text:
This is a project to add items to your Z brace rods without the need to take the rods off, or as standalone adjustable modular building blocks. It was specifically designed to mount a Raspberry Pi Zero and a Pi Cam onto the Z brace rods without any tools, nuts/bolts or other hardware. Fully printable. If you use your imagination you can use them for other things, too. The rods I have are 5/16 threaded rod.

A word of caution: Some of these parts are tricky to print. They rely on close tolerances to work. Play with your settings to achieve your desired results or adjust as you see fit.

I hope that y'all find some use for it. I've whipped up several additional pieces to broaden it's usability. The hex base, for instance, can be used to mount various pieces to in case you don't want to snap it to your Z brace rods. The Z clips will snap down tight. I've also included a screwdriver recess for easy removal.

This is a WIP and I've done my best to test them. They all work for me. Some post-processing will be required depending on your printer, filament, settings and overall printer tune.I don't plan to refine these much more as I have a list of other projects I'd like to move on to. But, if there is some glaring error I'll try to fix it. Other than that, feel free to adjust and modify to suit your needs or create additional parts to work with it.

title: Anet A8 Fan & Sensor Holder
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Several users had asked me if I could combine my sensor bracket https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1907394 with a holder for the extruder fan where you could easily remove the fan in order to get to the extruder gears.
I was pointed to this nifty idea designed by 85holmberg https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2326111 Thanks for the very practical design!

I took the idea merging both together by creating a new design.

This holder is designed to be used without the heat sink. My tests at 235°C nozzle and 95°C bed temperatures have shown that the lower portion of the extruder holding the nozzle throat remains cold as long as the fan is running.

Besides the benefit of easy to access to the extruder this modification will also reduce the mass of the extruder unit by 12.3 grams (0.44 ounces).

It weighs 5.6 grams when printed in ABS.

You will need two M3 x 25mm screws to mount the holder to the extruder motor.

  • Always make sure to retighten the two screws now and then since the filament material will deform over time! If that is not checked then the Z-offset could change.

Here are the settings to use with the Skynet3D V2.x Firmware:

Offsets for 12mm sensors:

  • X_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER -22 // X offset: -left +right [of the nozzle]
  • Y_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER -36 // Y offset: -front +behind [the nozzle]
    and
  • LEFT_PROBE_BED_POSITION 25
  • RIGHT_PROBE_BED_POSITION 195
  • FRONT_PROBE_BED_POSITION 20
  • BACK_PROBE_BED_POSITION 180

Offsets for 18mm sensors and for BLTouch:

  • X_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER -26 // X offset: -left +right [of the nozzle]
  • Y_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER -40 // Y offset: -front +behind [the nozzle]
    and
  • LEFT_PROBE_BED_POSITION 25
  • RIGHT_PROBE_BED_POSITION 194
  • FRONT_PROBE_BED_POSITION 20
  • BACK_PROBE_BED_POSITION 170

Please let me know if you have a problem with the design so I can improve it if necessary or you what new features to the design and ask before making any kind of remix.

Also please post a picture with comments if you have made one.

Thanks.

Leo

Update 2017.07.06

Added a version for use with a BLTouch "Anet_Fan_Sensor_Holder_BLT_Leo_N"
You will need two M3 screws.

Update 2017.08.13

Updated "Anet_Fan_Sensor_Holder_BLT_Leo_N" to accommodate the new version BLTouch-Smart.

Printer:

Anet A8

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

15% (lines)

Notes:

ATTENTION (2017.06.29):
If you plan on printing high temperature filaments (>80°C Bed, >220°C Extruder) then you will need to print the holder in either ABS, PETG or similar.
Long term tests have shown that when printed in PLA the holder WILL warp and the screws will loosen over time!

Print with 1.2mm (3 perimeters).

Use supports but only where it is touching the build plate!

description.text:
I liked the idea of a modular LED-Bow-Lamp from Opossums very much (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1703104) and was fascinated of this genious construction. But at the end it seems to be very lavish to me with a lot of costs for filament and print-time, so I thought about making it lots of easier with optimisation in material and time. It has to be more modular, easy to mount, not to glue, and flexible in many ways just by a few changes.

The result is what you see here:
A small module, easy to combine to achieve different shapes for a stable bridge-construction of customizable lenght. If you want, you can make straight or bended shapes, with one or two basis-stands. Build a bended desk-lamp with only one stand or use it as a bridge-construction to your modell-railway train when you flip it upside down.

Just build as much modules as you need, define the radius with the anchor-modules and put an LED-strip underneath to have a nice LED-lamp.
One of the basis-stands is made to contain the powersupply, the other one for the opposite, if you need it.

To combine the modules, just put a peace of 1.75-mm-filament into the hinge. No glueing, no other peaces required. Longer anchor-modules will give you a positive radius, shorter will effect in a negative way.

I'm not yet done with my own LED-lamp, but as soon as I'm finished, I will add photos of it.

If you like to play with the design, I attache the original FreeCAD-Files.
Experiment and have fun and please post your makings.

Antivibration mount to reduce "jelloing" of a GoPro mounted to a IRIS quadcopter from 3DRobotics. The standard GoPro mount is mounted on the front of the IRIS and, for my developer edition IRIS, is also rigidly mounted to the quadcopter frame. The rigid attachment of the camera allows vibration to distort the video. This bracket accepts standard GoPro attachments and moves the camera under the quadcopter closer to the CG. It also spreads the load so Velco can be used to attach it to the bottom of the quadcopter. The Velcro allows quick detachment and, since I use two layers of Velcro, provides a decent amount of vibration isolation. I attached the Velcro to the "Iris Tarot gimbal adapter" http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:196914 but the Velcro could also be attached directly to the bottom of the IRIS or any other quadcopter.

description.text:
"The Lords of the Beyond after being banished left behind a large strip of devastated land, with ghost towns, buildings, temples and a whole range of localities. Rumors that in these places existed treasures, weapons and a whole range of fantastic things, began to arrive in the ears of the people of our world.

Individuals in search of fame and fortune have decided to enter these cursed lands in search of these prizes. Organized in small groups, they enter these lands and there they face dangers. This is the premise of Scavengers, a skirmish game in the devastated lands, where you lead a group of adventurers in search of fame and fortune.

Extracted from Alabar Chronicle´s, a Scavenger Guide to Our World"

Introduction

Scavengers is a table top miniature war game for fighting skirmishes with fantasy/steampunk figures. Two players fight a small scale combat with five to ten miniatures on each side (a hero and your henchmen). The game is easy to learn and play, though there is enough depth that it will take time and experience to master.

The game was designed around three core premises.

a) You can download our 3D models or use any miniatures in their collection. Thus, the game is not specifically designed to any particular manufacturer or company. But if you like to help the game dev, please download our models! (They are free and paid...)

b) It is important that the miniatures on the table be the focus of the game. In the end, miniature gaming should be about miniatures (and fun!)

c) A large background - We´ll develop new units, histories and game scenarios. But we need your help, sending suggestions to improve the game!

I hope you like our game and have fun! Ahh, an important thing: this is the basic core rules, our idea is releasing other books to improve the game!

This is a Small Tower, for your game table! Our gaming site is coming with our core book, game lore and a lot of new things!

Note: You don´t need a base for it.

title: Whirligig Flying Spinner - Flies 30 ft (10 m)

description.text:
Pull the string and watch your Whirligig fly across the room.  Print 2 handles and pass back and forth with a friend.  Tilt at 45 degrees in the direction you want it to fly.
To launch, place the whirligig on the handle and wind the string.  Be sure to wind clockwise when viewed from the top of the whirligig/handle.
Also comes with a stick so you can launch with your hands, if you prefer that method.  Place the whirligig on the end of the stick and hold the stick between your hands with your hands flat.  Quickly push your right hand forward.  The whirligig will detatch from the stick and fly (you don't want the stick to stay in; the extra weight will cause it to not fly as far).
Stick launched version flies 20 ft (6 m).

When I first designed this, I did not think it would print, but it did and it flies well. Printers have trouble with 2 in bridges and 15 degree inclines in general, but the two together seem to work. String launched version: Requires 2 vitamins:
  • String about 3 ft (1 m) long. Tie a bowline knot with 1/4 inch (6 mm) diameter loop at one end. http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bowline
  • Nail roughly 2 inches (5 cm) long with 0.093 inch (2.4 mm) diameter shaft. For best results, flatten 1/4 inch (6 mm) from point with hammer (refer to the attached image). I used a blow torch to heat the tip to red hot to ease flattening (Be careful. Use pliers to hold the nail. Don't burn yourself). Flat portion should be 0.050-0.060 thick (1.3-1.5 mm). Nail shaft diameter is not critical. You may need to scale the nail clip to match your nail diamter. The scale option on your host software will work fine for this since no other dimention on the clip really matters.
    • Assemble as follows:
    Print whirligig, string handle, quick release, nail adapter, and nail clip (1 each). I used a 0.18 mm layer height.
  • Push the nail, flattened tip first, through the handle. The flattened tip should stick out the top of the handle.
  • Push the nail adapter on the flattened end of the nail. It should be a tight fit. If it is too loose or you opted to not flatten the end of the nail, use some glue. At this point the nail is trapped, the coupling prevents it from sliding out one way and the head keeps it from sliding out the other way.
  • Glue the quick release to the end of the nail adapter.
  • For ease of winding, snap the nail clip onto the nail between the two handle beams. This will probably need glue.
    • Start wrapping the string by putting the bowline loop over the nail clip and spin the nail. Stick Launched Version No vitamins required. Assemble as follows:
  • Print whirligig, stick, and quick release.
  • Glue coupling to stick.
    • Parts print fine with ABS or PLA. I have found ABS to work better for the whirligig because the PLA is brittle and breaks more easily when it impacts a wall. It does not matter what material you use for the non-flying portion.

title: Exoplanets sizes: TRAPPIST-1 versus the Solar System

description.text:
This is a script that generates models of the star and planets in a planetary system; I've used it to generate models for our solar system and for TRAPPIST-1, a system with many earth-like planets around a much smaller star. These models are to the same physical scale, so the (piece of the) Sun is in proportion to the star of TRAPPIST-1, as are all the planets.

The script is included and allows you to generate such models at any scale and of other planetary systems for which you know the sizes.

I recommend, as I did, printing TRAPPIST-1 in red rather than the yellow of the Sun, because TRAPPIST-1 is a much redder star - an ultracool dwarf. For more on TRAPPIST-1, see here or Wikipedia.

This thing is inspired by fc_tea's Sun and Planets to scale but I wrote the script from scratch and used planet details from Wikipedia, thus discarding any sensible aesthetic choices in the original.

Notes:

The small TRAPPIST-1 printed pretty well with no bottom and zero infill, in spite of the spheres, but the larger Solar System model failed badly even when I tried to skimp on the infills; the tricky part is where the planets stick out of a sloping part of the Sun: here you don't have a bridge and unsupported plastic sticks out over a void. A simple circular reinforcement below each of the larger planets would solve the problem, but I haven't implemented that.

The script is written in Python, using SolidPython to generate OpenSCAD files, which are then compiled to STL. I've included the generated OpenSCAD files, but they're really not meant for human consumption. The Python lives in an IPython notebook, and it should be pretty clear from the contents how to produce another stellar system (say Kepler-11, with its super-Earths).

Sodastream makes home drink carbonators and they use metal takes for the CO2, which come with green plastic caps to protect the threads (which are mostly but not quite exactly standard CO2 fittings).  The caps are easily lost or broken, and the are a generally awful green color (not unlike Thingiverse's STL renderer's default color).

Print in your favorite color.
SCAD file has several parameters which can be adjusted.  Two STLs are provided - one mimics the default green caps, the other has two larger handles instead of ridges for grip.
Can also be used to make other cylindrical caps.  Specify the diameter of the interior of the cap, plus the wall thickness, and optional handles.

This is Day 11 of my collection of printable equations. To see the whole collection, go to: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:227210 Based on plastic's request in the comments, (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:231587/#comments), for today's equation, I'm doing y = sin(cos(x/7)+sin(x))*x. I've included the Openscad file in case someone wants to modify the text or stand. Details:
  • There's a surprise guest in the pictures.
  • units are in mm
  • y scaled by 0.5 and x scaled by 1/9 to keep size reasonable
  • Range(x) = 0 to 200
  • I'm still using the original algorithm for creating the thick curve, which can produce artifacts at rapid changes in slope. I'm working on an improved algorithm that will filter out the artifacts, but haven't had time to finish it.
    • As always, I'm going to continue to post one equation per day until get bored or people lose interest. If there's a particular equation you'd like to see, leave a comment and I'll give it a shot.

description.text:
I am sure these have been made many times before, but i couldn't find any good ones so decided to make my own. This are the first 3D things i made but they work rather good.I use them for my ant colonies, but they should be usable anywhere. Now for the Important Stuff

IMPORTANT IMPORTANT

You can resize these to whatever size you need.

V2 - Interior diameter is 6mm. Version A is normal, Version B has holes to hang on a nail on the bottom. Hanging it works good although I haven't left it up for an extended period of time. This is the only version with the holes.

V4 and V5 - Interior diameter is 8mm. Works great with 1/4 inch tubing. The only difference between them is V4 is larger but both still have the same insert length. I would recommend V5 unless you need the 8 and up connectors.

The test piece is 8mm if you want to test the fit.

There may be some strange artifacts in some of the more complicated models, but they all should print fine. Let me know if anyone has any problems or requests.

title: Epic Scale Astartes Strike Cruiser Proxy

description.text:
An Astartes Strike Cruiser proxy model for Epic scale games (40k or armageddon etc).

[update 20171020: netfabb was playing today so all new fixed files]
[update 20171019: fixed some edge issues]

Requires superglue for assembly.

Looks a bit blocky in the stls but once you print it it kinda melts and softens a bit at this scale.

there is a full model stl file for viewing only (though it has now been fixed as well so should print)

the other 10 files (i will get around to naming them properly soon) contain segments of the ship and base and need to be assembled. the segment option is available in case your print jobs curl off the bed at the corners. no point printing something that looks like its gellar field failed.
my alignment of the bits is slightly off but nothing a solid dab of paint wont cure.

yes, the ship does balance quite well on the scatter base, i was surprised my own self.

Strike Cruisers only make a brief cameo on the table and aren't meant to be in any kind of relative scale. they're just a temporary marker while you deploy drop pods and so on.

Speaking of which, i'm not a fan of scatter dice do i've shamelessly stolen an idea from halo's tabletop offering.
place the model at the intended location, roll a d6; on 1 or 6 you don't scatter.
on 2,3,4,5 you scatter, so roll the die again. the result matches one of the 6 directions on the scatter base.
then roll 2d6 for scatter distance.

title: PLA Welding: Join PLA like a boss

description.text:
Cyanoacrylate super glues do not work on PLA.  Epoxies are a hassle, take a long time to set, and not as strong as the rest of your printed part.  Hot air tools melt too much material, make good joints very difficult to acheive, and cannot fill gaps.
For a strong, long lasting joint weld pieces together with a soldering iron using this rod as filler material.

Run your extruder as high as it will go and move the bed out of the way (position over a dump location).  Extrude 5 or 6 inches (12-15 cm) of filament (this is ussually called "purge" on your host software, you will only need to purge a few mm of 3 mm filiment to get the desired length of extruded filament.  Blow on the filament to cool it (if you don't have a fan) and pull it off of the extruder.  Repeat a dozen or so times.
The next time you need to join PLA, find an old cheap soldering iron or a worn out tip for your good one.  I used a cheap radio shack verion on "high" (40W) with a blunt damaged tip that can no longer be used for soldering.  Place a piece of rod along the joint.  Run over the joint with the soldering iron melting the rod and a small amount of both pieces to be be joined.  For joints with large gaps, repeat with more filler rod.
This method forms joints as strong or stronger than the printed part, fills gaps, and gives great control over how much material is melted.

I found, that a hard street and these rocket parts made from PLA falling from 15-20m height are quite incompatible. I'm working on a parachute which fits under the rocket tip - but haven't found a good solution, yet. Will tell you, when I have...

title: Drela AG27 Airfoil Micro Drone Propeller (34.68g thrust @ 3V)

description.text:
The drone propeller was inspired and designed by using the Drela AG27 airfoil. I tested it on the Drone Propeller Thrust Testing Jig (test results below).

It was printed at a slow speed, with a 0.2mm extruder nozzle at 0.04mm layer height. The print was cleaned with the help of a Precision Knife

After this, I got to finishing the part with a piece of 400 grit sandpaper.

These are the readings for a few voltage presets (you can also check these out in the images):

  • 1.5V => 12.71 grams
  • 2V => 20.88 grams
  • 2.5V => 28.45 grams
  • 3V => 34.68 grams

The included files consist of all pictures relevant to the test, with 6 text files that have all the airfoil coordinates used in the build, the printable STL files and the SLDPRT files. Should you want to print this propeller, make sure you get a 8520 coreless motor.

You can use the SLDPRT files, just in case you want to adapt the model to suit your needs.

Notes: The airfoil plotted with the matplotlib library in python.

Basic fidget spinner just for fun. ill give it a go printing later and may update the file depending on how that goes.

Its meant for a 608 bearing in the center and pennies on the out side. Its also covered in radii for your comfort as you fidget :D

This is a wedge I designed to fit the Polysher turn table to help coat vertical surfaces.

I found vertical surfaces don't get the same dissolving effect as horizontal. The idea is to rotate the model 180 degrees on this wedge halfway through the cycle.

There are 2 versions:

1.) Fixed angle
2.) Variable angle (base, table)

The idea behind the variable angle is that you can rotate the model without getting fingerprints on it. I also included a drain for the IPA to exit.

Enjoy!

Update 6/3/17:
You'll want to print the table in NinjaFlex or PolyFlex. I found with PLA even with a 10 degree angle the print slid off of the table. I wound up putting a dab of CA on a few of the standoffs and it held until the PVA softened up to tack it into place on it's own.

Overall, the approach was effective in getting mist to adhere to vertical surfaces. The cycle was spit in half (20/20), and the model rotated to 180 degrees to coat the other side. This is a must for tall, vertical models!

This is an aluminum one piece platform that incorporates an attachment point for a cable chain for the hot bed and thermistor wires.

The attached file is a .dxf file and is suitable for laser or water jet cutting.

I made mine from 5mm 6061-T6 aluminum. The corner holes are oversize rather than threaded and receive an 8mm counterbore to keep the leveling springs centered around the m3 screw. I also ran an m3 nylock nut on the m3 adjuster screw up tight to the heat bed. That centered the spring at the top and prevented the screw from spinning in the bed.

I now adjust the bed only from below and it requires very little tweaking. This way I do not have to remove the glass bed cover to make adjustments. I use the knurled bed adjustment knobs here https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2138298

Additionally there is the drag (cable) chain restrainer that snaps on over the platform frame edge. This is necessary to keep the cable chain from moving above the bed when moving in the -Y axis.

This is the cable chain that I used with this setup http://www.gearbest.com/3d-printer-parts/pp_268309.html . It comes in a 1 meter length, and less than half of that is required.
